## Plan

Add a validation block at the top of `POST /users` before the DB insert. No new dependencies needed — a simple regex covers email format.

Here's exactly what changes:

**`src/app.js` lines 6–10**, replace:

```js
app.post('/users', async (req, res) => {
  const { name, email } = req.body;
  const result = await db('users').insert({ name, email });
  res.status(201).json({ id: result[0], name, email });
});
```

with:

```js
app.post('/users', async (req, res) => {
  const { name, email } = req.body;
  const errors = [];
  if (!name || typeof name !== 'string' || name.trim().length === 0) {
    errors.push('name is required');
  } else if (name.length > 100) {
    errors.push('name must be 100 characters or fewer');
  }
  if (!email || typeof email !== 'string' || !/^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]+$/.test(email)) {
    errors.push('email must be a valid email address');
  }
  if (errors.length > 0) return res.status(400).json({ errors });
  const result = await db('users').insert({ name, email });
  res.status(201).json({ id: result[0], name, email });
});
```

**What each check does:**

| Rule | Check |
|---|---|
| `name` non-empty string | `typeof name !== 'string' \|\| name.trim().length === 0` |
| `name` max 100 chars | `name.length > 100` |
| `email` valid format | regex `/^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]+$/` |

Returns `400` with an `errors` array listing all failures. Should I apply this?

